    <title>You can escape this Royal Caribbean cruise aboard a virtual train ride</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="A rendered look a the Royal Railway Utopia Station immersive train experience restaurant." src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/eybU9N5DRVmNlLUGAohT0bJa_6Y=/0x1:1430x954/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73464638/royal_caribbean_cruise_train1.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;&lt;em&gt;On the Utopia of the Seas you can experience train dining without the bumps and spilled drinks.&lt;/em&gt; | Image: Royal Caribbean&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="ndphdP"&gt;The new 5,668-passenger &lt;a href="https://www.royalcaribbean.com/utopia-of-the-seas/"&gt;Royal Caribbean Utopia of the Seas&lt;/a&gt; is docked in Florida, where sites like&lt;em&gt; &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://go.redirectingat.com?id=66960X1514734&amp;amp;xs=1&amp;amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cruisecritic.com%2Fnews%2Fa-train-at-sea-royal-caribbean-lays-the-tracks-for-new-dining-experience&amp;amp;referrer=theverge.com&amp;amp;sref=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theverge.com%2F2024%2F7%2F16%2F24199880%2Froyal-caribbean-utopia-of-the-seas-cruise-trains-immersive" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Cruise Critic&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt; have gotten a preview of the amenities before it enters service on July 19th. That includes a unique experience called &lt;a href="https://www.royalcaribbean.com/cruise-dining/royal-railway-utopia-station"&gt;Royal Railway Utopia Station&lt;/a&gt;, where passengers dine on a virtual train ride while staring at simulated scenery zipping by on giant screens.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="WJDa2G"&gt;The restaurant is built to look like two full-size rail cars with a lavish interior featuring four-person booths lining the sides, each with its own giant display serving as a virtual window. What diners see out those virtual windows will rotate throughout the year. The first experience is Western-themed, with views of mountains, canyons, and gold rush towns.&lt;/p&gt;
